04816nam a22007455i 9780226552873DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017049038  a9780226552873  a(DE-B1597)521348  a(OCoLC)1029200370  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBX5620.D85bK53 2018 4aBX5620.D85bK53 2018eb 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a283.092aB223  aLB 546052rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90570:9821 aKlassen, Pamela E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Story of Radio Mind :bA Missionary's Journey on Indigenous Land /cPamela E. Klassen. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b6 color plates, 57 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- t1. The Medium Is the Medicine -- t2. A Life on the Border -- t3. Testimonies, Protocols, and Spiritual Stories -- t4. Picturing the Soul on Manidoo Ziibi -- t5. Map Is Territory -- t6. Printing Presses in the Promised Land -- t7. Frequencies for Listening -- t8. Truths and Reconciliations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the dawn of the radio age in the 1920s, a settler-mystic living on northwest coast of British Columbia invented radio mind: Frederick Du Vernet—Anglican archbishop and self-declared scientist—announced a psychic channel by which minds could telepathically communicate across distance. Retelling Du Vernet’s imaginative experiment, Pamela Klassen shows us how agents of colonialism built metaphysical traditions on land they claimed to have conquered. Following Du Vernet’s journey westward from Toronto to Ojibwe territory and across the young nation of Canada, Pamela Klassen examines how contests over the mediation of stories—via photography, maps, printing presses, and radio—lucidly reveal the spiritual work of colonial settlement. A city builder who bargained away Indigenous land to make way for the railroad, Du Vernet knew that he lived on the territory of Ts’msyen, Nisga’a, and Haida nations who had never ceded their land to the onrush of Canadian settlers. He condemned the devastating effects on Indigenous families of the residential schools run by his church while still serving that church. Testifying to the power of radio mind with evidence from the apostle Paul and the philosopher Henri Bergson, Du Vernet found a way to explain the world that he, his church and his country made. Expanding approaches to religion and media studies to ask how sovereignty is made through stories, Klassen shows how the spiritual invention of colonial nations takes place at the same time that Indigenous peoples—including Indigenous Christians—resist colonial dispossession through stories and spirits of their own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBishopsxBiographyxBritish Columbia. 0aBishopszBritish ColumbiavBiography. 0aBishops. 0aChurch work with IndiansxChurch of England in Canada. 0aMissionariesxBiographyxBritish Columbia. 0aMissionarieszBritish ColumbiavBiography. 0aMissionaries. 0aMissions, Canadian. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aIndigenous peoples.  aSettler-colonialism.  amaps.  amediation.  amissionaries.  aphotography.  aprinting presses.  apsychic research.  aresidential schools.  aspiritual politics.  astorytelling.  awhiteness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226552873423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226552873/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Ch